It’s easy to get lost in the echo of a vicious cycle and not realize it. Through words, how people treat us, and things that happen to us is how we accumulate injuries. These injuries shape us and sometimes those poison things become part of who we are. They come out in our words, and actions and they become the lens we see life through. We use those things against ourselves and other people and the cycle continues. 

I want to believe that we don’t have to become the sum of our injuries, but it’s easier. We can just blame other people for the way we are. It’s difficult to even recognize these things about ourselves and its arduous work to dig yourself out of an avalanche of a lifetime of damage. 
__

As a graphic designer and New Yorker, I had to share my thoughts on the new We ❤️ NYC logo. This is a bit late, but that’s because I would have written a novel if I had to write it down, so I made a video because that's more fun. The short of it is to think about the new logo as “just a rebrand” would be ignoring the logo's cultural impact. It has transcended far beyond NYC and NY state and may be one of the most parodied logos (way before that was cool). It has a deep significance to NYC and I think trying to “refresh it” was an impossible job given its history and the number of people involved on the client side. I’m not a fan of the new logo, but my reasons are far from “it’s ugly”. For more context and a closer look, check out my YouTube channel for the video. You’ll get a history lesson, maybe get inspired by Milton Glaser, hear my full opinion, and possibly get a laugh from some of the comments from NYers.
__
Lastly, in 2019 I was fortunate enough to meet Milton Glaser and work on a project that captured his thoughts on the I Love NY logo. Some footage from that project is also in the video.
__

I think it’s often misunderstood that confidence is just something some people have. Or, it’s something you just decide to have one day. I believe it’s a learned skill that ironically comes from failing a lot until you eventually figure it out, or at least become competent at something. Failing isn’t fun. It hurts your ego. But over time you grow thicker skin, let it go, and keep going. It comes from growth which might be the indicator between real confidence and someone pretending to be confident.

In a world full of “No’s”, you’re bound to find a “Yes” if you keep asking. I have a folder on my computer called “Nope”. All of my rejected applications to galleries and opportunities go in there including the things that I never get a response to…which is like  e v e r y t h i n g.
__
In January, something that I had put in that folder about 6 months prior didn’t belong in that folder anymore. I finally got a “Yes”. Duggal Gallery here in NYC asked me if I was interested in releasing a limited edition print with them. They’ve released prints with many people who’s work I admire including: @mattsiren, @epicuno, and @chrisrwk just to name a few.
__
So, if you feel like all you get is big “No’s” from everyone, believe me, I know what you mean. It can be demoralizing. What I’ve learned over the last decade is that you have to keep asking and putting yourself out there despite the rejection (or worse, no response!). 
__
My first limited edition print “The Future” will be released this Wednesday 4/12 at 2pm ET in collaboration with @duggal_gallery.
__
Photos by @mikebanom

Last week my Reddit Avatars, Halftones, launched! The art school kid in me loves a good concept, so here’s the thinking behind these. I based these on 3 of the 12 archetypes commonly found in literature and media. I selected these 3 as a commentary on some of the most common archetypes currently found in our society, specifically on the internet.
__
Neuetone - The Ruler
The rich, the privileged, the influencer. They fall into this role because their wealth and or money affords them the power to influence. With great power comes great responsibility.
__
Avantone - The Rebel
Highlights the divisiveness amongst people that keeps growing. This could be anyone who is outspoken that desires change no matter what their politics are. Choose your hill to die on wisely.
__
Voidtone - The Everyman
The regular everyday person. They don’t need to stand out, they just want to a purpose and have value in society. I chose to show this one more broken and fractured because I believe in general people are having a harder time finding their sense of purpose and finding meaning and stability in current times.
__
I’m sure most people collecting these will never look this deeply at them, but that’s okay.
__

Some scenes from yesterday at the group show opening at @188allenstreet.
__
The theme is Anti AI. Scraping art and data off the internet without artist's consent and no option to opt-out is theft. It's not inspiration. It's a means to feed a data set that can then be sold for access. Let's draw a parallel: Artists don't want their images and work fed into a data set because they don't want their hand/likeness to potentially be generated. Prompt artists (those who use AI) are secretive about their prompts because they don't want people to be able to generate things that are similar to what they've generated. If you can't see the hypocrisy here, you're willfully ignorant or you lack critical thinking skills.
__
I believe there are many good uses for machine learning models when they don't infringe on the rights of others. If an artist or a brand could build a data silo of their catalog of work (that they own the rights to) I think it could be a very powerful tool. Or, if they consent to having their work be included in a data set.
__
Special thanks to:
@mikebanom for the photography 
@sacsix for curating the show
__

Luck is a form of superstition often interpreted differently by different people. One can be "lucky" or "unlucky". Luck can be random, non-random, or influenced. I've always been intrigued by this and how every culture has its own perception of luck. I've created a few pieces exploring some of these ideas. The first is Make Your Own Luck.
__
Having a good luck charm is how some believe they can increase their luck. Carrying a rabbit's foot is considered to bring a person good luck. A surprising number of places worldwide believe this including Europe, China, Africa, and North and South America. However, how one obtains said lucky foot varies by region. One of the more popular takes is that it must be the left hind foot of a rabbit captured in a cemetery.
__
What do you think? Do you have a good luck charm?

Ready for some more luck superstitions? You've probably seen this lucky cat before. This calico Bobtail cat is known as Maneki-Neko, or 'Beckoning cat'. It's a common Japanese figurine believed to bring good luck to the owner. They're commonly displayed in restaurants, shops, hotels, laundromats, and other places of commerce. There's debate whether it originated in Tokyo or Kyoto, but it was sometime during the late 1800's.

There's a lot of folklore around the origin story of Maneki-Neko. According to one, an impoverished show owner took in a stray, starving cat despite having very little to share. As a form of gratitude, the cat sat at the front of the shop beckoning customers, bringing prosperity to the shop owner.

A raised left or right paw actually has different meanings. A raised left paw is to get more customers, while a right paw is to get more money.

Time for a change of pace with some bad luck superstitions. Break a mirror and you'll get seven years of bad luck. This superstition has been traced back to the ancient times of the Romans. They believed mirrors were devices in which the gods observed our souls. So to break one would be careless and disrespectful and 7 years of back luck would be the price to pay. Why 7 years? Because they also believed that the body renewed itself every 7 years.

You never know where the things you do will lead you or who they’ll resonate with. This year I had the opportunity to work with sticker companies like StickerApp and FireSprint. __
I'm not sure I believe anyone who says that anything is possible if you try hard enough. But I think constantly putting your work or yourself out there will increase the chances of you getting closer to what you want to achieve or some sort of opportunity. Or, in other words, maybe we get a little brighter with each spark of progress.

What you see isn’t all there is. I had been thinking about this a lot earlier this year. On the surface, this is an obvious observation. When you begin to look at everything thing through this framework you realize it’s true and it’s very overwhelming. Consider all of the thought, skill, and know-how behind a piece of design. Consider all of the technology and knowledge behind most things we interact with daily. Consider all of the millions of reasons people around you are doing what they’re doing and what led them there. There is so much going on behind everything. But then, consider all of the possibilities for yourself. If you don’t let yourself become paralyzed by it, it can almost be freeing. 
__
This is the art for my 3rd and final trading card in @thecreativestcp Series 3. All three use the theme of insects as symbolism to explore different broad perspectives about life.
